# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aukus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] The International Copyright Act of 1891 was the first U.S. congressional act that offered copyright protection in the United States to citizens of countries other than the United States.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] The act allowed the President to enter the United States in bilateral copyright treaties, extending copyright to the works of nationals from signatory countries and receiving copyright for the works of Americans in that signatory country.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] The act was passed on March 3, 1891, by the 51st Congress.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] The Act went into effect on July 1, 1891.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] On July 3, 1891, the first foreign work, a play called *Saints and Sinners* by British author Henry Arthur Jones, was registered under the act.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] Although international copyright protections are common now, and literary piracy is generally recognized as a crime, such broad-reaching protections have not always existed.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] In the decades following the American Revolution, it became common for works of British literature to be reprinted in the United States without any acknowledgment, authorization, or compensation given to the original author.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] Because of a lack of agreed upon international law at the time, this literary piracy was entirely legal, and the immense distance between the two nations made the issue difficult to address.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] The Statute of Anne, passed in 1710, was the first English law to provide for copyright regulated by the government and courts, rather than by private parties.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] This act protected the reproduction of British works produced by British Authors, but did not have any jurisdiction outside of the United Kingdom.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] In 1869, Edward Thornton, British minister to the United States, proposed the first international copyright laws between the United States and the United Kingdom to try and stem the spread of international literary piracy.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] This system fell into place largely because the nation did not have any real individual literary identity at that point in time.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] During that period, the United States was still in the early stages of its independent development as a nation and most of what the new American public was comfortable with involved British culture and ideas.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] These pirated novels had already established a reputation and success in England and were therefore not a risk to publishers in the States, who already knew that there would likely be a success in the New World.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] In some cases, these pirated novels were more accessible in America than they were to the British where they were originally printed.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] Although novels were a large portion of the pirated works from England, magazines, and newspapers were included in the stolen works as well.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] One primary example can be seen in *Harper's New Monthly Magazine*, a magazine that was aimed at women and attempted to create a patriotic attitude in the developing nation.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] Harper's ideas and strategies involved exposing these women to the British form of "elevated" culture in an effort to increase the standard and quality of the new American literature, which would result from the British inspiration they provided in their magazine.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] It was formerly believed that because of America's lack of a social class system, there would be no real need for a strong literary tradition.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] Harper's tried to expose the British tradition in order to facilitate growth for the American tradition.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] They sold for a low cost because there was no compensation being paid to the original authors back in England for the sole purpose of exposing every educated person in the new American public to "the unbounded treasures of the periodical literature of the present day".
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] The important thing was not the actual content of the magazines or their national origin but more about how much circulation and exposure these pieces received.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] This feeling of inspiration eventually backfired when the American authors were intimidated by the intense connection and dependence on British authors and did not produce many.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] Eventually, the resentment for the lack of Americanism led to a change in Harper's to include more national, not international, authors.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] This change never really paid off and the magazine did not see the same amount of success and profit that it received from the British pirated material.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] During the time when the United States was just beginning to develop its own literary tradition, the nation refused to protect foreign works.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] As a result, American works were unprotected abroad and domestic publishers had to compete with each other for cheap editions of foreign works.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] Prior to the International Copyright Act, the first national copyright law was passed in 1790 and provided a copyright protection for 14 years, but only for authors who were citizens or residents of the United States.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] In order to get copyright protection in the rest of the world, American authors were required to gain residency in the country in which they desired copyright protection.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] For example, Mark Twain obtained residency in Canada to protect his publication of *The Prince and the Pauper*.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] To protect foreign literature in the United States, British authors would have an American citizen serve as a collaborator in the publishing process, and then have the book registered in Washington, D.C., under the collaborator's name.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] It was not until the 1830s that the pressure to extend American copyright to foreign authors first developed.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] Both American and British authors and publishers joined forces and pushed for a bilateral treaty between the United States and England.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] Famous authors such as Charles Dickens came to the United States to show their support for international copyright.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] Their biggest problem were American printers that already were protected by a high tariff on imported works, and who had no wish to pay royalties to English writers or publishers.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] The United States discussed international copyright with Great Britain over the years.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] Congress requested correspondence to this effect in 1842.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] There was a proposed treaty in 1853 under Millard Fillmore, and consideration of its ratification continued into an extension provided during Franklin Pierce's presidency in 1854.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] Nonetheless, in the United States, only works published in the United States could be restricted with copyright.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] Authors including Mark Twain, Louisa May Alcott, Edward Eggleston, and Bill Nye wrote letters in the mid-1880s to the *Century* requesting international copyright.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] These letters to the journals had a strong effect on this issue, as did the American Copyright League that was formed in 1883.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] The league was a great supporter of an International Copyright Act and, at the Madison Square Theater in 1885, the league sponsored readings by American authors in aid of the League's cause.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] In 1885, United States Senator Joseph Roswell Hawley introduced a bill aimed at extending copyright to foreign authors for consideration by Congress.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] A chief difference between the Hawley Bill and the eventual Chace Bill was Hawley's removal of publisher and book-sellers' interests in the copyright process.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] It was ultimately unsuccessful, though Mark Twain involved himself in the lobbying process and influenced President Grover Cleveland's thinking on the matter.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] Cleveland asked Congress for legislation to this effect in his State of the Union address that December.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] In 1884, academics, writers and diplomats met in Berne, Switzerland, to draft the multilateral copyright treaty eventually known as the Berne Convention.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] The treaty was signed in 1886 but the United States was not one of its founding members.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] American representatives had attended the Berne conference only as observers and it would take another 5 years until the United States took its first step to protect foreign works.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] Ever since the first national copyright law in 1790, the United States had required certain "statutory formalities" to acquire copyright protection.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] These formalities served as a test of an author's intention to claim protection for his or her work.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] The International Copyright Act of 1891 now applied these formalities to foreign publishers as well, but added an extra requirement called the "Manufacturing Clause".
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] The Manufacturing Clause required that all copies of foreign literary works should be printed from type set in the United States if they were to have American protection.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] This was an obvious concession to American printers, since they might otherwise have opposed the Act.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] This would then allow American publishers time to release an authorized edition.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] The International Copyright Act of 1891 instituted important changes in copyright matters.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] One of the most extensive changes was that from the date the Act went into effect, all books were required to be manufactured in the United States in order to obtain American copyright.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] However, foreign authors had a better chance of protecting their works than before.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] This Act was the first step that the United States took towards an international copyright that could benefit foreign authors as well as domestic.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] Throughout time, the United States had been somewhat of a copyright outcast since they had not joined many international treaties or conventions.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] However, as the United States became a major exporter of copyrighted materials this changed.
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] Berne Convention, Universal Copyright Convention, WIPO).
[src:aukus/18th-century-american-piracy-of-british-literature] The Copyright Act of 1909 had its own prescriptions for extending copyright to other countries.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] In the incident, the two USAF A-10s fired on and destroyed two Blues and Royals armored vehicles, killing one British soldier, and wounding five others.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] Although not the only fratricide incident during the invasion, the circumstances of the inquest into the death of British lance-corporal of horse Matty Hull – and the subsequent verdict of unlawful killing – led to much media scrutiny in the UK.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] This was related to the release of video evidence from the attacking aircraft, and perceived levels of cooperation by government agencies of both the United States and United Kingdom with the British inquest.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The Blues and Royals were serving as an armoured reconnaissance element for 16th Air Assault Brigade.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] Four vehicles from D Squadron, two FV107 Scimitars and two FV103 Spartans, were moving north of the main force, patrolling the Forward Edge of Battle Area.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The area of the patrol had been declared as a *no engagement zone* to the allied forces and the vehicles were marked with the agreed coalition Combat Identification markings including orange overhead canvas panels, thermal reflectors and Union Flags.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] Two A-10 Thunderbolt II aircraft of the Idaho Air National Guard, 190th Fighter Squadron (call signs POPOV35 and POPOV36) were completing a two-hour mission; engaging artillery and rocket launchers of Iraq's 6th Armoured Division, dug in 25 miles (40 km) north of Basra.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The aircraft were guided to their targets by US Marine Corps forward air controllers, embedded with British ground units, and flown by a major and a lieutenant colonel on their first operational flight of the invasion.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] According to media reporting of the subsequent investigation, the flight was commanded by the major.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] From an altitude of 12,000 ft (3,700 m), the aircraft spotted Iraqi vehicles 800 yards (730 m) north, and the British patrol less than three miles (5 km) west.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] Following dialogue with the Forward Air Controller (FAC) and between the aircrew, the British convoy was engaged by the A-10s in a gun and rocket attack which left the vehicles disabled.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The British soldiers exited the vehicles, taking cover underneath the hulls.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The aircraft conducted a second attack, resulting in the death of lance-corporal of horse (L/CoH) Matty Hull, still within his Scimitar.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] Trooper Christopher Finney, 18, driver of the lead Scimitar, re-entered his burning vehicle calling a Mayday report on his still-functional radio.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] Trooper Finney then dragged a badly wounded L/Cpl Tudball from the burning vehicle before attempting to recover Hull in the second Scimitar, but being beaten back by exploding munitions and heat.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] As well as the death of Hull, a further five soldiers were injured.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The US Air Force conducted an investigation into the incident in 2003, but the results of that investigation were not publicly released, and did not result in a court-martial.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] Higher United States Department of Defense officials, however, cleared both pilots of any wrongdoing.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] A British Army Board of Inquiry (BoI) was held in 2004, the findings of which, among others, stated that the major authorised the lieutenant colonel to attack, but no authorisation was given by controllers on the ground.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The report was released to the family of Lance Corporal Hull and later to the public.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] It has been alleged that certain classified material available to the BoI was withheld from the family.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] At the time, the bodies of those service personnel dying overseas were repatriated to the UK via RAF Brize Norton, leading to the responsibility for inquests being under the civilian jurisdiction of the Oxfordshire coroner.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] An inquest into the death of L/CoH Hull was convened in 2006, presided over by Assistant Deputy Coroner Andrew Walker.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The stated position of the United States government is that US servicemen do not attend non-US courts, with written statements normally being provided.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] British media reported that the UK government had pressured the US government, via the US embassy in London, to release all evidence related to the incident.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] A meeting between Constitutional Affairs Minister Harriet Harman and Deputy Head of Mission, David Johnson, was reported on 20 November 2006 where assurances were given that concerns of the UK government over the US policy on attendance were to be relayed to Washington.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] Harman reiterated this position on 1 February 2007, highlighting the request for evidence and indicating that the US personnel could not be compelled to attend the inquest.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The inquest took oral testimony from the various British personnel associated with the incident, including those in the convoy, and a FAC who expressed the opinion that the aircrew were acting independently.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] Walker commented on the actions of L/Cpl Finney GC, stating: *"You are a brave man.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] It was publicly acknowledged during the inquest that a cockpit video of the head-up display from one of the aircraft existed, which media reports indicated had been shown to the BoI, but not released to Hull's family with the findings.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The video was shown to the coroner in private, although permission to use it in public was refused by the Ministry of Defence, citing international agreements related to the release of classified information, and the US classification of the tape as secret.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] This adherence to international protocols led to significant criticism in the British media, leading to a public statement by Armed Forces Minister Adam Ingram which reiterated the requirement for US de-classification of the video and highlighting ongoing engagement to achieve that.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] Media reporting indicated that the MOD had previously denied the existence of the video.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] On 2 February 2007 Walker opted to adjourn the inquest until the video could be displayed in open court.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The video was leaked to *The Sun* tabloid newspaper, and reported on 6 February 2007, as well as published on the newspaper's website.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The newspaper indicated that the leak had come from a US military source.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The US government subsequently announced that the video would be declassified, but noted that the leak was likely to be a criminal offence.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The video released was 19 minutes long, and was accompanied with recordings of cockpit audio and radio communications.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] Neither pilot gave the precise grid references for the Household Cavalry patrol to double check its identity.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The pilots convinced themselves that the orange identification panels were in fact orange rocket launchers.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] POPOV36 decided to attack, saying he is "rolling in" without permission from the Forward Air Controller.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] POPOV35 asked for artillery to fire a marker round into the target area to clear up confusion, but POPOV36 attacked without waiting for it.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] POPOV36 strafed the column for a second time, but still doubted its identity.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The audio track includes debate over the identity of the targets and the order, from the FAC, to disengage identifying a likely "blue-on-blue" incident.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The audio track also includes notification of one death and several injuries with the order to return to base.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] Subsequent audio indicates the pilots crying and their frustration.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] A statement released by the Oxfordshire coroner's office later confirmed that Walker was of the view that, being in the public domain, the video could now be presented as evidence without the approval of the US government, and that the inquest would resume on 12 March 2007.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] On 6 February 2007 the *Sun* named POPOV36 as Colonel Gus Kohntopp, a commercial pilot for Southwest Airlines and member of the Idaho Air National Guard.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] However, POPOV35, the one who gave the order: “Get him, get him,” has never been publicly identified.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The British inquest was set to resume on 12 March 2007.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The Oxfordshire inquest resumed as scheduled on 12 March with testimony from a British FAC involved in the incident, who stated that the incident would not have happened if the two U.S. pilots involved had followed the same procedures that UK pilots must follow in the same type of situation.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] Bush for the information to be released to the inquest.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] On 16 March, coroner Andrew Walker returned a narrative verdict, stating that the killing of Hull was "unlawful".
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] Walker said: "The attack on the convoy amounted to an assault.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] It was unlawful because there was no lawful reason for it and in that respect it was criminal." Neither of the two U.S. pilots involved nor any other representative from the U.S. government appeared at the inquest, despite numerous requests from Walker, Harman, and Hull's family to do so.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] As a rare case where video of an incident of fratricide or 'friendly fire' has become publicly available, the case has attracted a great deal of interest among researchers interested in exploring the question of why such incidents occur and what might be done about them.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] In the course of their research, Elsey, Mair, Smith and Watson developed an alternative version of the transcript, based in part on the detailed information released in the USAF Friendly Fire Investigation Board Report, to make it easier to follow the incident's interactional dynamics.
[src:aukus/190th-fighter-squadron-blues-and-royals-friendly-fire-incident] The transcript is available open access.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] The first ever flight from the United Kingdom to Australia, sometimes known as **The Great Air Race**, took place in 1919.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] Of the six entries that started the race, the winners were South Australian brothers Ross and Keith Smith, serving as pilot and co-pilot respectively.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] They were also accompanied by mechanics James Bennett and Wally Shiers, all of whom made the successful journey of 14,350 kilometres (8,917 mi; 7,748 nmi) from London to Adelaide in a modified Vickers Vimy bomber.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] One other entrant reached Australia; the other four crashed en route, two of whose crews were killed.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] Although the race had finished upon reaching Australia in Darwin, an extra leg of 3,290 kilometres (2,044 mi; 1,776 nmi) to the Smith brothers' hometown of Adelaide was undertaken.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] The prize-winning Vickers Vimy aircraft is displayed in a climate-controlled museum of the same name, in Adelaide Airport.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] In early 1919, the Commonwealth Government of Australia offered a prize of £A10,000 for the first flight from Great Britain to Australia in a British aircraft, under specific conditions.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] The departure point must be either Hounslow Heath Aerodrome (for landplanes) or RNAS Calshot (for seaplanes and flying boats), with reporting points at Alexandria and Singapore, and final destination in the region of Darwin.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] Each flight was to take place under the competition rules of the Royal Aero Club, which would supervise the start and control the competition generally.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] At 11:44 a.m. on 21 October 1919, Captain George Campbell Matthews AFC as pilot, and Sergeant Thomas D.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] Kay as mechanic, took off from Hounslow Heath Aerodrome in a Sopwith Wallaby (G-EAKS).
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] Bad weather caused delays at Cologne and Vienna, then they were imprisoned as suspected Bolsheviks in Yugoslavia, with further delays due to snow at Belgrade.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] A cracked engine cylinder at Constantinople, and bad weather at Aleppo caused more delays.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] Finally, on 17 April 1920, the Wallaby crashed on landing at Grokgak, on Bali.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] Vickers entered a converted Vimy bomber (G-EAOU) (the registration being whimsically said to stand for "God 'elp all of us"), crewed by Captain Ross Macpherson Smith with his brother Lieutenant Keith Macpherson Smith as co-pilot and mechanics Sergeant W.H.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] The Vimy left Hounslow Heath at 8:30 a.m. on 12 November 1919.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] The flight distance was estimated as 17,911 kilometres (11,129 mi) and total flying time was 135 hours 55 minutes (131.8 km/h or 81.9 mph).
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] The prize money was shared between the Smith brothers and the two mechanics, with the Smith brothers additionally receiving a knighthood for this exploit, the company presented their aircraft to the Australian government.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] It is now displayed at Adelaide Airport, 15 kilometres (9 mi) south of the Smith brother's birthplace, Semaphore.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] On 13 November 1919, Lieutenant Roger M.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] Ross took off from Hounslow Heath in an Alliance P.2 Seabird (G-EAOX) named 'Endeavour'.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] It crashed in an orchard in Surbiton; Ross was killed outright, and Douglas died soon after of his injuries.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] A team with a Blackburn Kangaroo (G-EAOW) had selected as navigator the Australian aviator Charles Kingsford Smith.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] Smith withdrew from the contest, and Captain Hubert Wilkins MC and bar took his place.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] On 21 November 1919, the Kangaroo took off from Hounslow Heath, piloted by Lieutenant V.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] Rendle with Captain Wilkins, Lieutenant D.R.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] Problems were experienced with the engines, and the plane was forced down over France.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] Repairs were made and the flight continued, still with engine problems.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] On 8 December 1919, the aircraft crash-landed at Suda Bay, Crete, ending up against the fence of a mental hospital.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] Howell and Lieutenant George Henry Fraser left London in a Martinsyde Type A Mk.I (G-EAMR) aircraft.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] On 9 December, the aircraft disappeared near Corfu.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] The wreckage and Howell's body were found offshore, but Fraser's body was never found.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] On 8 January 1920, Airco DH.9 (G-EAQM), piloted by Lieutenant Ray Parer, with co-pilot Lieutenant John Cowe McIntosh, took off from Hounslow Heath.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] The aircraft completed the flight, the first by a single-engined machine, 206 days later on 2 August 1920, earning Parer the sobriquet "Battling Ray".
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] Although outside the time limit, the crew was awarded a consolation prize of £A1,000, second only to the Vimy.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] The DH.9 has been restored and placed on display at the Australian War Memorial at Canberra.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] The story is detailed in the book "Flight and Adventures of Parer and McIntosh" written by Emily Charnwood and first published in 1921.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] The machine is labelled PD after its sponsor, millionaire Peter Dawson, a whisky manufacturer, who financed the purchase of the machine and much of the journey.
[src:aukus/1919-england-to-australia-flight] Parer later took part in a similar journey, the MacRobertson Trophy Air Race in 1934.
[src:aukus/1976-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] From 6 to 11 July 1976, Queen Elizabeth II made a state visit to the United States with her husband, Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, during the celebration of the bicentennial of the American independence.
[src:aukus/1976-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] She was received by President Gerald Ford on 7 July 1976.
[src:aukus/1976-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] The visit marked the second time she undertook a state visit to the United States as monarch.
[src:aukus/1976-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, arrived in Philadelphia on 6 July 1976 and after carrying out some engagements spent the night abroad the royal yacht HMY *Britannia*.
[src:aukus/1976-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] The arrival ceremony took place on 7 July, after which the Queen presented President Ford with "a soup tureen that featured a painted image of the White House and Independence Hall" which later went on display at the Smithsonian Institution.
[src:aukus/1976-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] The President and the First Lady in return presented the Queen and the Duke of Edinburgh with a bronze statue by Harry Jackson depicting cowboy Calyton Danks astride the horse Steamboat.
[src:aukus/1976-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] The state banquet was held in the Rose Garden in a tent.
[src:aukus/1976-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] At the request of the Queen, Bob Hope and Telly Savalas were invited for the entertainment portion of the banquet in the East Room.
[src:aukus/1976-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] First Lady Betty Ford described the Queen as "easy to deal with.
[src:aukus/1976-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] She was very definite about what she wanted and what she didn't want." On 8 July, the Queen visited the U.S.
[src:aukus/1976-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] Capitol and the Smithsonian before hosting a banquet at the British Embassy in Washington, D.C..
[src:aukus/1976-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] On 9 July, the Queen and the Duke sailed into New York Harbor abroad the royal yacht after carrying out engagements in New York City held a banquet on the royal yacht and subsequently left for New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:aukus/1976-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] On 10 July they disembarked at New Haven before flying from Tweed-New Haven Airport to Charlottesville, Virginia.
[src:aukus/1976-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] 50,000 people lined the docks, streets and the airport to see the couple during their brief stop in New Haven.
[src:aukus/1976-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] They then departed Charlottesville for Newport, Rhode Island, and sailed overnight to Boston.
[src:aukus/1976-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] On 11 July they carried out engagements in Boston before departing for Canada.
[src:aukus/1976-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] Her visit to Boston was marked by a 21-gun salute, and in the North End she met with Governor Michael Dukakis before having lunch with Mayor Kevin White at City Hall.
[src:aukus/1976-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] The Queen and the Duke also greeted the crowds from the balcony of the Old State House.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] From 14 to 26 May 1991, Queen Elizabeth II, made a state visit to the United States with her husband, Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] The visit marked the third time she undertook a state visit to the United States as monarch and it was her fourth official visit overall.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh were formally welcomed on the South Lawn of the White House by President George H.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] The UK and U.S. national anthems were played during the military ceremony accompanied by firing of gun salutes to mark the occasion.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] The Queen also inspected the Guard of Honor.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] During the visit, she planted a little-leaf linden on the South Lawn.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] The Queen then visited the Arlington National Cemetery and laid a wreath the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] A state dinner was served in the royal couple's honor on the night of 14 May.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] On 15 May, the Queen toured northeast Washington, D.C. and attended a lunch at a celebration of British film and television.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] On the same day, she attended a garden party on the grounds of the British embassy.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] The President and the First Lady then took the Queen and the Duke to a game of Baltimore Orioles.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] On 16 May, the Queen watched *King Lear* acted at the Folger Shakespeare Theater and *The Taming of the Shrew* at the Fillmore School.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] The Queen addressed a joint session of Congress on 16 May 1991, becoming the first British monarch to do so.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] Subsequently, she visited Miami and Tampa in Florida, Austin, San Antonio, and Houston in Texas, and Lexington in Kentucky.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] The Queen's visit to Florida began on 17 May when she arrived at the Miami International Airport.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] Her engagements included a visit to Booker T.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] Washington Middle School, a brief garden party at Vizcaya Museum and Gardens, and a dinner and black tie reception abroad HMY *Britannia* attended by former presidents Ronald Reagan and Gerald Ford.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] A small protest by the Irish American Unity Conference took place as the event was going on.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] The Queen and the Duke also visited Fort Jefferson.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] The royal couple visited the MacDill Air Force Base and in a private ceremony the Queen made General Norman Schwarzkopf Jr. an honorary Knight Commander in the Military Division of Most Honourable Order of the Bath.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] The visit to Texas began on 20 May, the first time that a British monarch had set foot in the state.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] Governor Ann Richards and former first lady Lady Bird Johnson toasted the monarch at a formal reception and dinner at the Lyndon B.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] The Queen also addressed the Texas State Legislature.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] On 21 May, the royal couple landed at Kelly Air Force Base for a visit to San Antonio where they saw San Antonio River, met with local dignitaries at the Institute of Texan Cultures, and visited the Alamo Mission.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] They then arrived at Dallas Love Field and the Queen stayed at the Adolphus Hotel before visiting the Morton H.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] Meyerson Symphony Center and the Hall of State at Fair Park to honor the 150th anniversary of Dallas.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] On 22 May, the royal couple then toured NASA Johnson Space Center in Houston and visited a VA Medical Center, the Museum of Fine Arts, and Antioch Missionary Baptist Church.
[src:aukus/1991-state-visit-by-elizabeth-ii-to-the-united-states] The Duke of Edinburgh returned to England and for the final leg of the tour the Queen visited Kentucky horse farms to make breeding arrangements for her mares.
[src:aukus/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The **1993 United Kingdom–United States Maritime Boundary Treaties** are two treaties between the United Kingdom and the United States which established a maritime boundary between British territories and American territories in the Caribbean Sea.
[src:aukus/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] Both treaties were signed in London on 5 November 1993.
[src:aukus/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The first treaty delimits the boundary between the British territory of Anguilla and the United States Virgin Islands.
[src:aukus/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The boundary is a simplified equidistant line that consists of a single maritime straight-line segment 1.34 nautical miles (2.48 km; 1.54 mi) long.
[src:aukus/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] It is defined by a straight line connecting two individual coordinate points.
[src:aukus/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The full name of the treaty is *Treaty between the Government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland and the Government of the United States of America on the Delimitation in the Caribbean of a Maritime Boundary between the US Virgin Islands and Anguilla*.
[src:aukus/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The second treaty delimits the boundary between the British Virgin Islands and the United States Virgin Islands and Puerto Rico.
[src:aukus/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The boundary is a simplified equidistant line that runs in a south–south-east direction until it terminates at the tripoint of Anguilla.
[src:aukus/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] It is far longer and more complicated than the Anguilla–U.S.
[src:aukus/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] Virgin Islands boundary: it is about 200 nautical miles (370 km; 230 mi) long and consists of 49 straight-line segments defined by 50 individual coordinate points.
[src:aukus/1993-united-kingdom-united-states-maritime-boundary-treaties] The two treaties entered into force on 1 June 1995 after they had been ratified by both states.
[src:aukus/1news] Broadcast from its Auckland studios, 1News' nightly 6pm bulletin is usually New Zealand's most-watched television programme and seen as influential.
[src:aukus/1news] TVNZ operates bureaus in Auckland, Wellington and Christchurch and has foreign correspondents based in Australia, Europe and the United States.
[src:aukus/1news] Television news in New Zealand began in 1960 with the introduction of television broadcasting.
[src:aukus/1news] News bulletins were produced separately in Auckland, Wellington, Christchurch and Dunedin, as the country's television stations initially operated independently due to the lack of a permanent national network.
[src:aukus/1news] Although temporary nationwide links could be established for major events, these required extensive advance planning and could only originate from predetermined locations.
[src:aukus/1news] National news and current affairs programmes produced in Wellington were copied onto videotape and flown to the other centres for broadcast, often resulting in significant delays.
[src:aukus/1news] Plans for a nationwide television network were developed from 1967.
[src:aukus/1news] The proposed system would link the four main centres using a combination of microwave and off-air relay stations, allowing programmes to be broadcast simultaneously throughout the country from any of the major studios.
[src:aukus/1news] The sinking of the passenger ferry *Wahine* in April 1968 highlighted the limitations of the existing system.
[src:aukus/1news] Footage filmed in Wellington could not be broadcast simultaneously in other centres, and the extra-tropical cyclone associated with the disaster grounded aircraft, preventing videotapes from being flown around the country for later transmission.
[src:aukus/1news] In October 1969 the nationwide TV network was completed, using a mixture of microwave and off-air broadcast links.
[src:aukus/1news] The first network news broadcast was live on 3 November 1969 at 7:35pm, read by Dougal Stevenson; the programme was called the *NZBC Network News*.
[src:aukus/1news] Initially, it was read by Philip Sherry, Dougal Stevenson or Bill Toft on a rotating roster.
[src:aukus/1news] Because the microwave network was not yet fully complete, footage from outside Wellington had to be inserted by manually switching between transmitter feeds.
[src:aukus/1news] During these changes, viewers briefly saw a black slide carrying a letter in the top-right corner, usually hidden by television overscan.
[src:aukus/1news] The letter identified the source channel and signalled transmitters when to switch feeds.
[src:aukus/1news] Prior to the building of the Warkworth satellite communications station in 1971, international programmes could not be received live – the footage had to be flown into New Zealand and was often days old.
[src:aukus/1news] The *NZBC Network News* featured many other newsreaders until the NZBC was dissolved in 1975.
[src:aukus/1news] The programme was then renamed as simply *News*.
[src:aukus/1news] While the NZBC began broadcasting in colour on 31 October 1973, *Network News* continued to primarily broadcast in black-and-white until the NZBC was dissolved on 31 March 1975.
[src:aukus/1news] This was to avoid refitting the Wellington studio in Waring Taylor Street with colour equipment while awaiting the move to the new purpose-built Avalon television centre.
[src:aukus/1news] TV One began broadcasting on 1 April 1975 and moved its evening news bulletin to 6:30 pm, with Dougal Stevenson or Bill McCarthy reading the news on a rotating roster until 15 February 1980.
[src:aukus/1news] The launch of TV One also coincided with the opening of the Avalon television centre, allowing the news to broadcast primarily in colour.
[src:aukus/1news] TV2 followed suit on 30 June 1975 and its main evening news was initially broadcast at 7 pm before moving to the earlier timeslot of 6 pm by the end of 1975.
[src:aukus/1news] Jennie Goodwin was the first female newsreader in New Zealand to anchor a nightly television news programme, although Angela D'Audney was the first two years earlier.
[src:aukus/1news] TV One and South Pacific Television were amalgamated into Television New Zealand on 16 February 1980 and its main evening news continued to broadcast at 6:30 pm on TV One.
[src:aukus/1news] Initially, these programmes aired at 7:30 pm and ran for half an hour in duration.
[src:aukus/1news] In February 1982, the main bulletin was revamped and broadcast from 6:30-7:30 pm; the one-hour package incorporated the day's national and international news, regional news programmes and the weather forecast.
[src:aukus/1news] In late 1983, *Nationwide* was dropped, with the main bulletin extended to fill the time and give greater sports news coverage.
[src:aukus/1news] During the mid-1980s, Philip Sherry and Tom Bradley shared the role of newsreader on a rotating roster with Richard Long and Tony Ciprian alternately presenting sports news.
[src:aukus/1news] Weather was presented on alternate nights by Veronica Allum and Sue Scott.
[src:aukus/1news] The main bulletin was revamped in November 1986 and renamed as the *Network News*, with Judy Bailey and Neil Billington initially co-presenting in a double-headed format and replacing Philip Sherry.
[src:aukus/1news] Tom Bradley moved to weekends, where he alternated with Angela D'Audney as weekend anchor.
[src:aukus/1news] In February 1988, sports anchor Richard Long took over from Neil Billington as co-anchor of the *Network News*, the beginning of a partnership that would continue for much of the next 15 years.
[src:aukus/1news] Tony Ciprian moved to the new commercial network TV3, the network's first sports producer.
[src:aukus/1news] He was with *3 News* for almost 20 years.
[src:aukus/1news] In July 1988, the *Network News* was moved to 6 pm and renamed as the *Network News at Six* but the weekend bulletin remained at 6:30 pm (as the *Network News and Sport*).
[src:aukus/1news] The moving of the *Network News* to 6 pm also marked the introduction of computer-generated weather graphics and the arrival of Jim Hickey and Penelope Barr, who replaced Veronica Allum and Sue Scott as weather presenters.
[src:aukus/1news] On 3 April 1989 TVNZ launched a new nightly current affairs programme, *Holmes*, which was presented by Paul Holmes.
[src:aukus/1news] At the same time, the duration of the *Network News at Six* was reduced back to 30 minutes and the regional news programmes were transferred to around 5:45 pm on TV2.
[src:aukus/1news] The year saw the introduction of TVNZ's first foreign correspondents – Liam Jeory in London and Susan Wood in Sydney.
[src:aukus/1news] In October 1989, the weekend *Network News and Sport* was moved from 6:30 pm to 6 pm.
[src:aukus/1news] In November 1989, the *Network News* was relaunched as *One Network News*; its renaming due to competition from new broadcasting station TV3's news programme *3 National News*.
[src:aukus/1news] In December 1989, both *Top Half* and *Today Tonight* were axed by TVNZ but *The Mainland Touch* and *The South Tonight* continued for another year and screened on TV One at 5:45 pm as a lead-in to *One Network News* at 6 pm, with support from NZ On Air.
[src:aukus/1news] The Christchurch and Dunedin based regional news programmes were axed at the end of 1990.
[src:aukus/1news] In February 1995, the main bulletin was again extended from 30 minutes to a full hour, screening from the now familiar 6 pm timeslot, followed by *Holmes* at 7 pm.
[src:aukus/1news] The change coincided with the unveiling of a new studio set which was used until 2003.
[src:aukus/1news] On 2 January 1995, the main *One Network News* bulletin was delayed for 10 minutes after protesters occupied the studio and protested about the Māori language bulletin *Te Karere* which was off air over the Christmas and New Year period.
[src:aukus/1news] July 1997 saw the replacement of weekend news presenters Angela D'Audney and Tom Bradley with husband and wife Simon Dallow and Alison Mau.
[src:aukus/1news] Bradley resigned, but D'Audney stayed as a backup presenter for other bulletins until her death in 2002.
[src:aukus/1news] On 11 August 1997, the early morning *Telstra Business* and *Breakfast* shows were first aired; Telstra Business was hosted by Michael Wilson; Breakfast hosted by Susan Wood and Mike Hosking.
[src:aukus/1news] In 1998, TVNZ signed *3 National News* anchor John Hawkesby to replace Richard Long from the start of 1999.
[src:aukus/1news] But when Haweskby began presenting *One Network News* at 6 pm alongside Judy Bailey, there was a public outcry over the separation of Bailey and Long, that lead to Long reinstated as co-anchor at 6 pm three weeks later.
[src:aukus/1news] Hawkesby later took TVNZ to court, a dispute that he subsequently won.
[src:aukus/1news] The programme was renamed again on 31 December 1999 to *One News*.
[src:aukus/1news] On 19 March 2000, TVNZ launched its first digital initiative nzoom.co.nz.
[src:aukus/1news] Staffed by 20 journalists, nzoom included news, sports, entertainment and home and garden sections, in additional to being a web portal.
[src:aukus/1news] The website was closed in 2003, and replaced by a more basic offering that was designed to extend television programming.
[src:aukus/1news] At the time of its closure, it ranked second amongst local online news providers - behind the New Zealand Herald and ahead of Stuff.
[src:aukus/1news] 2003 saw a major shake up of TVNZ's news and current affairs programming with entering head Bill Ralston making sweeping changes to the formats of many programmes.
[src:aukus/1news] A new state-of-the-art studio came into use for *One News* programmes, but many presenters were culled.
[src:aukus/1news] The changes saw the end of Long and Bailey's 15-year partnership; from January 2004, the main 6 pm bulletin reverted to a single-headed broadcast with Judy Bailey as anchor.
[src:aukus/1news] Jim Hickey, TVNZ's most popular weather presenter, and sports presenter April Bruce (née Ieremia) also left in 2003.
[src:aukus/1news] In October 2005, TVNZ announced that it would not be renewing long-standing flagship broadcaster Judy Bailey's contract; some observers believe this was a direct reaction to the programme's market share decline in Auckland to *3 News*.
[src:aukus/1news] An emotional Bailey signed off for the final time at the end of the 6 pm *One News* bulletin on 23 December 2005.
[src:aukus/1news] She was TVNZ's longest serving newsreader and had been reporting and presenting with both NZBC and TVNZ for 34 years.
[src:aukus/1news] When the 6 pm edition of *One News* returned after the Christmas break of 2005–2006, it reverted to double-headed presentation with Wendy Petrie and Simon Dallow taking over from Bailey.
[src:aukus/1news] The weekend 6 pm bulletin remained single-headed until September 2008, when popular presenter Peter Williams joined Bernadine Oliver-Kerby as co-anchor.
[src:aukus/1news] In December 2008, One News relaunched online news product under the TVNZ.co.nz domain.
[src:aukus/1news] The broadcaster said it was "upping the ante" for digital offerings.
[src:aukus/1news] Sir Paul Holmes returned to TVNZ as the host on the new political programme *Q+A* in 2009.
[src:aukus/1news] He hosted the programme until late 2012, when illness prevented him from continuing his duties.
[src:aukus/1news] On 3 November 2009, TVNZ celebrated One News' 40th birthday with some archival footage available on their website.
[src:aukus/1news] Later that year, Jennie Goodwin, David Beatson, Dougal Stevenson and Lindsay Perigo returned to read one *Breakfast* news segment each.
[src:aukus/1news] A Saturday edition of *Breakfast*, called *Saturday Breakfast*, was broadcast from 3 September 2011, hosted by Rawdon Christie and Toni Street, and ran until the end of 2012, when it and *One News at 4:30* were cancelled for financial reasons.
[src:aukus/1news] 1News was awarded Best News in the Qantas Media Awards from 2008 through 2011 and won Best Breaking News in the New Zealand Film and Television Awards 2012.
[src:aukus/1news] In September 2012 an announcement was made that TVNZ would discontinue *Close Up* at the end of 2012.
[src:aukus/1news] The final *Close Up* programme screened on 30 November 2012 and in early 2013, an announcement was made of the replacement show, named *Seven Sharp*.
[src:aukus/1news] The first show screened on 4 February 2013.
[src:aukus/1news] Former BBC meteorologist Daniel Corbett joined the weather team in September 2014.
[src:aukus/1news] In December 2014, Jim Hickey left his position as head weather forecaster.
[src:aukus/1news] Nearly a year later Karen Olsen left the weathercaster position, making her final broadcast on 16 November 2015.
[src:aukus/1news] In July 2015, TVNZ rebranded its news website to One News Now, focused specifically on breaking news and video content.
[src:aukus/1news] The change was expected to double the website's number of video views.
[src:aukus/1news] Some changes were criticised for an apparent pivot towards "clickbait".
[src:aukus/1news] In May 2016, TVNZ began syndicating news video with Stuff.
[src:aukus/1news] One News programmes were renamed 1News in 2016, when TV One was renamed TVNZ 1.
[src:aukus/1news] During the COVID-19 pandemic in New Zealand as part of cost-cutting measures, 1News reverted to a single news presenter for its 6 pm bulletin.
[src:aukus/1news] Simon Dallow remained as the sole newsreader while Wendy Petrie lost her role.
[src:aukus/1news] Petrie would remain at TVNZ as a backup presenter across other 1News programmes.
[src:aukus/1news] Paul Yurisich, who was appointed to the role of Head of News and Current Affairs in 2020, resigned from TVNZ in 2022 after a review into the hiring of former Al Jazeera presenter Kamahl Santamaria.
[src:aukus/1news] Phil O'Sullivan replaced Yurisich as the Executive Editor, News and Current Affairs.
[src:aukus/1news] O'Sullivan had previously been in the role in an acting capacity since June 2022.
[src:aukus/1news] In late July 2023, 1News revamped its intro and banner, by changing the colour from blue to black, and moving the name and job to the left side.
[src:aukus/1news] In early March 2024, TVNZ proposed ending several television programmes including "1News at Midday" and "1News Tonight" due to a decline in advertisement revenue and competition from digital competitors such as Netflix and YouTube.
[src:aukus/1news] In addition, TVNZ has proposed 68 job cuts, amounting to about 9 percent of its staff.
[src:aukus/1news] On 9 April, TVNZ confirmed that 1News' Midday and late night bulletins would be axed by mid-May 2024.
[src:aukus/1news] Midday broadcast its final bulletin on Friday 3 May 2024, hosted by Indira Stewart.
[src:aukus/1news] On 7 October 2024, TVNZ's management proposed closing down 1News' website by February 2025 as part of a NZ$30 million cost-saving measure.
[src:aukus/1news] On 29 October, TVNZ abandoned plans to shut down its 1News website but proposed expanding the news content of its TVNZ+ streaming service.
[src:aukus/1news] On 26 January 2026, 1News updated its template with minor changes to graphics.
[src:aukus/1news] On 10 May 2026, 1News further advanced its appearance with a new opening, a new desk and a refreshed background including a virtual studio and purple colour scheme instead of their traditional blue.
[src:aukus/1news] BNZ Business Breakfast airs at 6:00am, 30 minutes, Before *Breakfast*.
[src:aukus/1news] Mei Heron will bring together business news, market updates, and expert perspectives to help make sense of the day ahead.
[src:aukus/1news] The bulletin has five segments separated by advertisement breaks.
[src:aukus/1news] National and international news stories for the first three segments (approximately 35 minutes), sport news in the fourth segment (approximately 10–15 minutes) with weather at the end.
[src:aukus/1news] with the full show starting from 6:30am.
[src:aukus/1news] Discontinued in July 2012, when TVNZ 7 closed down.
[src:aukus/1news] Discontinued in 2013 due to lack of funding.
[src:aukus/1news] During the COVID-19 pandemic in New Zealand a 1News Special was broadcast most days at 1 pm.
[src:aukus/1news] During the 1 pm broadcast Director-General of Health Ashley Bloomfield would announce how many new cases of coronavirus were in New Zealand.
[src:aukus/1news] The following is a list of 1News reporters.
[src:aukus/1news] This list does not include reporters from *20/20*, *Q+A*, *Fair Go*, *Sunday*, *Te Karere*, *Marae*, *Breakfast* and *Seven Sharp*.
[src:aukus/1news] TVNZ has one of the largest news gathering teams in the country – based in New Zealand and in TVNZ bureaus around the world.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] AUKUS is widely seen as a response to the perception among its members that the People's Republic of China poses a threat to the Indo-Pacific region.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The Chinese government said, when the partnership was announced, that it risked "severely damaging regional peace" and had a "cold-war mentality".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] A direct result of the creation of the partnership was Australia's controversial cancellation of a French-Australian submarine contract worth €56 billion (A$90 billion).
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The Australian government only gave the French government a few hours' notice of this before the public announcement of AUKUS.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The Australian government agreed to a €555 million (US$584 million) compensation settlement with French defence contractor Naval Group.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] In 2009, two years after the start of the project to replace the Royal Australian Navy's conventionally-powered *Collins*-class submarines, the Australian Defence White Paper stated: "The Government has ruled out nuclear propulsion for these submarines".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The design was based on the latest French nuclear-powered attack submarine, the Barracuda class, which required converting the nuclear propulsion to conventional propulsion.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Another difference was that Australia chose to equip it with a United States Navy combat system and torpedo with Lockheed Martin Australia selected to integrate them into the design.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Australia typically requires that part of their vessels be built there, which increases the cost.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] In this case it corresponded to 60 per cent of the contract value, with France handling the technology transfer.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] In 2019, Australia signed a strategic partnership agreement with Naval Group to design and construct twelve submarines to be built in Australia.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] However, the project was beset by delays and cost overruns, leading to uncertainty and tension behind the scenes.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The revised cost, including inflation during the length of the program, was A$90 billion (€56 billion).
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] In February 2021, an initial design plan was rejected as being too expensive, and Naval Group were given until September to improve their proposal.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] At a Senate inquiry in early June 2021, with delays ongoing, Defence Secretary Greg Moriarty revealed under questioning that he had considered making contingency plans if the French project was to fail, admitting that there had been ongoing problems for over a year.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Two weeks later, Australian prime minister Scott Morrison met French president Emmanuel Macron in Paris and expressed concern about the project going off track, to which Macron replied that France was giving "full and complete" commitment and would proceed "further and faster if possible".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Less than three weeks later, Australia decided to publicly cancel the contract with Naval Group for the *Attack* class submarines despite having already spent about A$2.4 billion on the French project.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] It was expected that Australia would have to pay hundreds of millions of euros in penalties for cancelling the contract.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The contract contained "control gates" with "off-ramps" at which point Australia could withdraw from the contract.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The Australian Department of Defence wrote to Naval Group on the same day the security partnership was announced.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The French Ministry of Defence claim the department told them that "they were satisfied with the submarine's achievable performance and with the progress of the program." Naval Group said that Australia "terminated the contract for convenience".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Morrison said that Australia now required a nuclear-powered submarine which has clear advantages of greater endurance, speed, power, stealth and carrying capacity than a conventionally-powered submarine, based on changes in the strategic situation in the Indo-Pacific.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] However, Johnson later told parliament that the move was not intended to be "adversarial towards any other power".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] United States secretary of state Antony Blinken and United States secretary of defense Lloyd Austin said that Australia did not have any "reciprocal requirements" as a consequence of the US sharing nuclear submarine propulsion technology such as Australia hosting intermediate-range missiles.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Under the partnership, the US and UK will share nuclear propulsion technology with Australia, as they have done with each other since 1958 under the US–UK Mutual Defence Agreement.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The Royal Australian Navy (RAN) will acquire at least eight nuclear-powered submarines armed with conventional weapons.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The basic design and key technologies will be decided by the Australian Nuclear-Powered Submarine Task Force an 18-month Department of Defence research project headed by Vice Admiral Jonathan Mead, begun in September 2021 with assistance from the US and UK.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Australia will extend the life of its *Collins* class submarines that the *Attack* class was due to replace and may consider leasing or buying nuclear-powered submarines from the US or the UK in the interim until the delivery of its future nuclear powered submarines.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Also in the interim, Australian Defence Minister Peter Dutton said that Australia will have regular visits by US and UK nuclear-powered submarines.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Australia considered purchasing French nuclear submarines which use nuclear reactors fuelled by low-enriched uranium at less than 6%.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] However, French reactor designs have to be refuelled every ten years, and Australia does not have a civil nuclear capability with nuclear energy prohibited.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] In contrast, American and British designs power the submarines for the expected life of the submarines using nuclear reactors fuelled by highly enriched uranium (HEU) at 93% enrichment.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Currently, six countries have nuclear submarines, the five permanent members of the UN Security Council (China, France, Russia, the United Kingdom and the United States) and India.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The New York Times reported that Australia will probably buy HEU from the US for the nuclear reactor that powers the submarine.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The United States' naval reactors are all pressurized water reactors (PWR).
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The latest UK propulsion system is the Rolls-Royce PWR3 that will power the Royal Navy's (RN) new *Dreadnought*-class submarines currently being built and is "based on a US design but using UK reactor technology".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] US officials have said that sharing nuclear propulsion technology with Australia is a "one-off" and that they have no "intention of extending this to other countries".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] South Korea, also a US treaty ally, has had ambitions to acquire nuclear-powered submarines since 2017 and was reportedly refused US assistance in September 2020 because of nuclear non-proliferation.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] On 22 November 2021, Australia, the US and the UK signed the *Exchange of Naval Nuclear Propulsion Information Agreement* (ENNPIA) treaty.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The treaty permits the disclosure of information by the US and the UK to Australia and its use.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The US is restricted by the Atomic Energy Act of 1946 from sharing information without an agreement and the UK is also restricted by the 1958 US-UK Mutual Defence Agreement unless authorised.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The treaty was considered in Australia by the Parliament's Joint Standing Committee on Treaties, in the UK by the Parliament and in the US by Congress.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The ENNPIA treaty entered into force on 8 February 2022.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] On 31 August 2022, the UK announced that Australian submariners would receive training aboard *Astute*-class submarines.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] On 13 March 2023, AUKUS announced that a new nuclear powered submarine class would be built in the UK and Australia to be called the SSN-AUKUS, also known as the SSN-A.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The US intends to sell Australia three nuclear-powered *Virginia* class submarines, subject to congressional approval, to ensure there is no capability gap as the *Collins* class submarines are retired, with the potential to sell up to two more if needed.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] RAN personnel will be embedded in the RN and USN to receive nuclear training and at UK and US submarine industrial bases.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The SSN-AUKUS class will based on the UK SSNR design already under development.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The RN is planned to receive its first SSN-AUKUS class submarine as early as the late 2030s.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The RAN is planned to receive their first submarine in the early 2040s.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Australia will reportedly build five SSN-AUKUS submarines.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The RAN is planned to receive their first *Virginia* class submarine from the US in the early 2030s.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The Australian Submarine Agency was established on 1 July 2023.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] It has the role of managing the Australian nuclear submarine program, and includes personnel posted to the UK and US.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Lincoln Reifsteck USN, the USN's AUKUS integration and acquisition program manager, talked at the Naval Submarine League's annual symposium.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] He said that, in 2032 and 2035, the US will sell to Australia in-service Block IV *Virginia* class submarines, the first of which was commissioned in 2020, and the final will likely commission around 2026.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Thus, Australia would receive submarines with between six and 15 years' worth of use, out of their designed service life of 33 years.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] He also said that the US would sell a new Block VII boat to Australia in 2038, the Block VIIs being the original *Virginia* class length without the Virginia Payload Module, set to begin construction in FY2029.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] In August 2024, Australian prime minister Anthony Albanese, made undisclosed "political commitments" with its AUKUS partners in an agreement for the transfer of naval nuclear technology to Australia, sparking concerns about the potential for high-level radioactive waste to be stored in the country.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The White House confirmed that Australia, the UK, and the US reached a significant milestone in their cooperation, essential for Australia's future nuclear-powered submarine capabilities.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Despite assurances from the government, critics, including the Greens, warned of possible loopholes that could lead to uranium enrichment and radioactive waste management in Australia.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] On 1 June 2025, the UK government announced that it will build up to twelve SSN-AUKUS submarines to replace the Royal Navy's seven *Astute-*class attack submarines from the late 2030s.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The announcement also said that there will be a major expansion of industrial capability at BAE Systems Submarines at Barrow and at Rolls-Royce Submarines at Derby, with a new boat scheduled to be built every eighteen months.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] On 26 July 2025, the UK and Australian governments signed the **Geelong Treaty**, a 50-year bilateral defence agreement to facilitate bilateral cooperation on the construction of Australia's SSN-AUKUS submarines.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] On 30 May 2026, at an AUKUS Defence Minister's Meeting held in Singapore it was announced that the third *Virginia-*class boat that Australia is planned to receive will now be an in-service Block IV boat the same as the first two.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] This will simplify fleet training and maintenance for Australia and save them significant costs.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] AUKUS Pillar 2 encompasses a wide array of activities (including many commonly referred to by the US Department of Defense as international armaments cooperation).
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] There may include information and personnel exchange, cooperative research, development, testing, and evaluation, and joint production.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] In contrast to Pillar 1 activities, which will take decades to deliver results, Pillar 2 is likely to produce more immediate capability improvements.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Undersea capabilities, in the context of AUKUS, refer to systems and technologies that operate underwater but are not crewed submarines.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The Defence Minister's meeting on 30 May 2026 announced that the first signature project of Pillar 2 would be cutting-edge sensors, payloads and weapons systems for UUVs with delivery to commence in 2027.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] As part of the Quantum Technologies working group, the AUKUS nations have established the AUKUS Quantum Arrangement (AQuA), an initiative to coordinate U.S., British, and Australian RDT&E efforts concerning quantum technologies.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Initial AQuA efforts were expected to focus on developing alternate solutions for position, navigation, and timing (similar to current Global Positioning System capability) through trials and experimentation through 2025.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The announcement of AUKUS included the stated aim of improving "joint capabilities and interoperability.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] We've always been interoperable, but this aims at much more.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] From artificial intelligence to advanced technology the US, UK and Australia will now be able to cost save by increasing platform sharing and innovation costs.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] *Engineering & Technology* also pointed to the March 2021 statement of the US National Security Commission on AI, of the imperative to intensify local efforts but also "rally our closest allies and partners to defend and compete in the coming era of AI-accelerated competition and conflict".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Under the partnership, the three countries will cooperate to accelerate development of hypersonic missiles and defence against such missiles.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Hypersonic and counter-hypersonic cooperation was one of four additional areas of cooperation announced on 5 April 2022.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Australia and the US have been cooperating on the development of hypersonic missiles since 2020 after signing an agreement to "flight test full-size prototype hypersonic cruise missiles" under the Southern Cross Integrated Flight Research Experiment (SCIFiRE).
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] In addition, the U.S., British, and Australian governments have established a number of initiatives designed to support Pillar 2 efforts as a whole, such as the AUKUS Advanced Capabilities Industry Forum and the AUKUS Defense Investors Network.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Since the announcement of "Pillar II" of AUKUS, there has been persistent speculation that Japan will eventually join the partnership; American Ambassador to Japan Rahm Emanuel wrote that Japan was "about to become the first additional Pillar II partner" in *The Wall Street Journal* on 3 April 2024.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] On 7 April 2024, the *Financial Times* reported that AUKUS defence ministers will announce on 8 April 2024 that they will launch talks related to the expansion of Pillar II of the alliance.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] In September 2024, the leaders of Australia, the UK and the US issued a joint statement announcing that AUKUS partners and Japan were exploring opportunities to improve interoperability of their maritime autonomous systems as an initial area of cooperation.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] New Zealand has agreed to officially explore the potential benefits of joining Pillar 2.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] In March 2023, New Zealand's defence minister Andrew Little said New Zealand had been offered the opportunity to discuss joining AUKUS for the non-submarine co-operation areas.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] New Zealand has indicated it was "willing to explore" the proposal.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] In July 2023, US Secretary of State Antony Blinken told New Zealand reporters that the “door is open” for New Zealand, as well as other countries, to join the security partnership.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] In December 2023, following the formation of a new government, Prime Minister Christopher Luxon said that New Zealand was open to joining the non-nuclear pillar of the AUKUS agreement during a state visit to Australia.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] In February 2024, Australia agreed to brief New Zealand on Pillar 2 developments following a joint bilateral meeting between Australian and New Zealand foreign and defence ministers in Melbourne.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Australian Defence Minister Richard Marles confirmed that Australia would send officials to brief their New Zealand counterparts on Pillar 2.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The four ministers also issued a joint statement expressing concerns about human rights violations in Xinjiang, Tibet and Hong Kong.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] In response to the joint Australian-NZ bilateral meeting, the Chinese Embassy in Wellington issued a statement deploring critical statements about China's internal affairs and describing AUKUS as "counter to the letter and spirit of the international nuclear non-proliferation regime".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] In September 2024, the leaders of Australia, the UK and the US issued a joint statement announcing that they were consulting with Canada, New Zealand, and South Korea to identify possibilities for collaboration on advanced capabilities under AUKUS Pillar II.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty allows non-nuclear-weapon states to produce the highly enriched uranium for naval reactor fuel.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Nevertheless, the agreement to transfer US or UK nuclear submarine technology including possibly highly enriched uranium has been described as an act of nuclear proliferation, and has been criticised by scholars and politicians.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] In the *Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists*, scholar Sébastien Philippe criticised AUKUS and wrote "we can now expect the proliferation of very sensitive military nuclear technology in the coming years, with literally tons of new nuclear materials under loose or no international safeguards".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Acton of the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace wrote that "the nonproliferation implications of the AUKUS submarine deal are both negative and serious.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] For Australia to operate nuclear-powered submarines, it will have to become the first non-nuclear-weapon state to exercise a loophole that allows it to remove nuclear material from the inspection system of the International Atomic Energy Agency.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] I have no real concerns that Australia will misuse this material itself, but I am concerned that this removal will set a damaging precedent.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Australia and Brazil would be the first countries without nuclear weapons to have nuclear-powered submarines.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] This would not apply in the case of Brazil because the reactor will use low enriched uranium at 7% concentration.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] 20% is the minimum level required to make a nuclear weapon.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Former Labor prime minister Paul Keating condemned the deal, saying "This arrangement would witness a further dramatic loss of Australian sovereignty, as material dependency on the United States robbed Australia of any freedom or choice in any engagement Australia may deem appropriate".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Former Labor prime minister Kevin Rudd warned against overly obtrusive criticism of China and recommended that Australia focus on quietly improving military capability.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Former Liberal prime minister Malcolm Turnbull, who had signed the original deal for the *Attack* class submarines called the decision to scrap the deal "an appalling episode in Australia's international affairs and the consequences of it will endure to our disadvantage for a very long time".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] He called the actions of his successor as deceitful and that it would damage Australia as foreign nations would no longer be able to trust Australia.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Abbott said that Australia would be safer as a result, and cited China's increasing naval firepower as a justification for the deal.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The Australian defence minister at the time, Peter Dutton, responded by saying that Australia wanted peace and stability and "an opportunity for Indonesia, Vietnam and Sri Lanka and Korea to continue to develop".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Dutton further dismissed "outbursts from China" and said that Australia was a "proud democracy" committed to "enduring peace and this collaboration makes it a safer region ... no amount of propaganda can dismiss the facts".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Australian Greens leader Adam Bandt criticised the deal, saying that it escalates tensions in the region and "makes Australia less safe".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Prime Minister at the time, Boris Johnson, said that the deal would create "hundreds of high-skilled jobs" and "preserve security and stability around the world" but said that the relationship with France was "rock solid".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Conservative MP Tom Tugendhat said: "After years of bullying and trade hostility, and watching regional neighbours like the Philippines see encroachment into their waters, Australia didn't have a choice, and nor did the US or UK [to make the deal]".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Former prime minister Theresa May questioned whether the UK would be forced into a war with China should Taiwan be invaded.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Johnson responded to French anger on 21 September by saying "I just think it's time for some of our dearest friends around the world to prenez un grip about this and donnez-moi un break"; the latter being broken French for "get a grip and give me a break".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] In 2026, the Defence Select Committee inquiry on AUKUS found that the political leadership of the programme had faded and that the UK commitment to *Astute*-class submarine visits to Australia had placed severe pressure on the overstretched Royal Navy.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] Responsibility for AUKUS had been transferred from the Cabinet Office to the Ministry of Defence, though the view that Prime Ministerial leadership would be important to maintaining the political impetus to deliver AUKUS was reported.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] The MOD had forecast that the UK nuclear workforce (defence plus civil) will need to increase by 40,000 by 2030 to support AUKUS and the wider demands on the Defence Nuclear Enterprise.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] To 2026, the UK government had committed £16 billion to developing AUKUS: long lead components for SSN-AUKUS, BAE and Rolls-Royce plant upgrades, and the Rolls-Royce nuclear reactors for submarines.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] It noted that trilateral progress on advanced technology under Pillar 2 had been inadequate and was losing credibility.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] President Joe Biden stated that the deal was a way to "address both the current strategic environment in the (Indo-Pacific) region and how it may evolve".
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] After a call between the French and US presidents, the White House acknowledged the crisis could have been averted if there had been open consultations between allies.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] It was agreed the process would continue in such manner.
[src:aukus/aukus-p01] In June 2025, the United States Department of Defense launched a review to inform whether to modify or cancel the AUKUS agreement with Australia and the United Kingdom, after a push by the Under Secretary of Defense for Policy, Elbridge Colby.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] On 12 April 2022, *Sankei Shimbun* reported that the United States, United Kingdom, and Australia were inquiring about Japan's participation in the security framework of AUKUS.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] The newspaper added that the aim of said negotiations was related to the incorporation of Japanese hypersonic weapon development and the strengthening of electronic warfare capabilities.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] The US denied inviting Japan into the security alliance, with Jen Psaki stating that Sankei Shimbun's report was "inaccurate".
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] This was followed by another denial from Hirokazu Matsuno, the Japanese chief cabinet secretary.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] On 10 December 2022, Australia's Minister for Defence announced their desire for Japan to join the partnership.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] On 14 March 2023, Japanese prime minister Kishida Fumio expressed his support for Australia's planned acquisition of US-made nuclear-powered submarines under the AUKUS partnership.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] The French government received official notification from Australia that the *Attack* class submarine project was to be cancelled only a few hours before it was publicly announced.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] *Le Monde* reported that the original cost of the project in 2016 was €35 billion of which €8 billion (A$12 billion) was to go to French companies.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] The project was reportedly going to employ 4,000 people in France over six years at Naval Group and its 200 subcontractors.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] The French government was angered by both the cancellation of the *Attack* class submarine project and not being made aware of the negotiations that led to the AUKUS agreement.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] In a joint statement, French foreign minister Jean-Yves Le Drian and armed forces minister Florence Parly expressed disappointment at Australia's decision to abandon their joint submarine program with France.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] On 31 October 2021, at the G20 summit in Rome, Macron was asked whether he thought that PM Morrison lied about the French submarine contract, to which Macron responded "I don't think, I know".
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] The French Ambassador also criticised Morrison on the basis that he lied about the former contract.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] Le Drian further stated in a radio interview that the contract termination was a "stab in the back".
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] On 17 September, France recalled its ambassadors from Australia and the US, Jean-Pierre Thébault and Philippe Étienne respectively.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] Despite tension in the past, France had never before withdrawn its ambassador to the United States.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] In a statement, Le Drian said that the "exceptional decision is justified by the exceptional gravity of the [AUKUS] announcements" and that the snap cancellation of the submarine contract "constitute[d] unacceptable behaviour between allies and partners".
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] French president Emmanuel Macron has not commented but is reported to have been "furious" about the turn of events.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] In response to questions about the Australia-EU trade deal currently being negotiated, French secretary of state for European affairs Clément Beaune stated that he doesn't see how France can trust Australia.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] Arnaud Danjean, a French MEP, said that "Australians can expect more than a delay in concluding the Free Trade Agreement with the EU".
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] French Lowy Institute policy analyst Hervé Lemahieu said the diplomatic damage from the cancellation will take years to repair and leave a lasting legacy of mistrust".
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] After a call between the French and US presidents, the French ambassador returned to the US on 30 September.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] Beaune described the United Kingdom as a junior partner and vassal of the United States due to the partnership, saying in an interview: "Our British friends explained to us they were leaving the EU to create Global Britain.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] We can see that this is a return into the American lap and a form of accepted vassalisation." Le Drian stated that "We have recalled our ambassadors to [Canberra and Washington] to re-evaluate the situation.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] So there is no need to bring our ambassador back to explain." A Franco-British defence summit was cancelled.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] Some opposition politicians in France, such as Xavier Bertrand, Jordan Bardella, and Fabien Roussel, criticised the French government and demanded that France leave NATO, with Christian Jacob as well as demanding a parliamentary inquiry.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] A foreign ministers meeting between France, Germany, the UK, and the US had been postponed, and a ministerial meeting between Australia, France, and India was cancelled.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] France however, contacted India to talk about strengthening their cooperation in the Indo-Pacific.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] France's foreign commerce minister declined a meeting with his Australian counterpart.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] French president Macron said that Europe needs to stop being naïve when it comes to defending its interests and build its own military capacity.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] Following the ousting of Scott Morrison's government after the 2022 Australian federal election, the new Labor government led by Prime Minister Anthony Albanese agreed to a €555 million (US$584 million) settlement with French defence contractor Naval Group.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] In response, French defence minister Lecornu said that France aims to rebuild its relationship with Australia.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] In addition, Albanese announced plans to travel to France to reset bilateral relations between the two countries.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] The exclusion of France from AUKUS has been conceptualised within the longue durée of the fractious relationship between France and the Anglosphere, potentially reducing scope for coordination in the Indo-Pacific in the short term.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] Zhao also said "The three countries should discard the Cold War zero-sum mentality and narrow geopolitical perspective".
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] Spokesperson Hua Chunying said "China is firmly opposed to the US, the UK and Australia's malicious exploitation of loopholes in the Nuclear non-proliferation treaty and the International Atomic Energy Agency safeguards mechanism".
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] It further told Australia to avoid "provocation" or else China would "certainly punish it with no mercy", and concluded "Thus, Australian troops are also most likely to be the first batch of western soldiers to waste their lives in the South China Sea".
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] The PRC ambassador to France Lu Shaye urged the new alliance to fulfill their nuclear non proliferation obligations and said Asia-Pacific needs jobs, not submarines, and urged France to boost cooperation.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] President of the European Commission Ursula von der Leyen told CNN that "one of our member states has been treated in a way that is not acceptable. ...
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] We want to know what happened and why." The EU also demanded an apology from Australia.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] President of the European Council Charles Michel denounced a "lack of transparency and loyalty" by the US.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] The EU said the crisis affects the whole union.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] Preparations for a new EU-US trade and technology council between the US and EU were postponed.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] France eventually dropped their opposition to these talks which took place in Pittsburgh on 29 September 2021.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] France also attempted to delay the free trade talks between the EU and Australia.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] Key advocates for the TTC talks included EU's digital chief Margrethe Vestager, who favors open markets, and EU trade chief Valdis Dombrovskis from Latvia, who views the US alliance and NATO as a vital counterweight to Russia and China.
[src:aukus/aukus-p02] Lithuanian deputy European Affairs Minister Arnoldas Prankevicius proclaimed "What is important is to keep trans-Atlantic unity, because we believe this is our biggest strength and biggest value, especially vis-à-vis such countries as Russia and China".
